pullRequest.bodyText:
Closes #5353. See my original post, since I make references to it here.
I wrote an example solution that applies Option 2 to exception #1, #2 and #5, Option 2a to exception #4, and Option 1 on the other exceptions. This means there are 2 constants and 4 if blocks worth of extra code from the base solution. When I talk simplicity vs accuracy, I made the file 2 constants and 4 if blocks less simple to make 18 names more accurate, but that begs the question: was that effort worth implementing? I chose these exceptions as a proof of concept of what "extra" code means, and they seemed the most simple to handle. (Some exceptions, using option 2, would use dicts maps, which hinders simplicity quite a bit; I wouldn't prefer to use maps.)

commit.message:
screenshot: fix method for naming quest complete screenshots

Current code assumes only one text format in the quest reward scroll and
 trims the text based on that assumption. The new code anticipates all
 possible text formats, present and future, and extracts the quest name
 based on regex pattern matching. This limits the possible number of
 incorrect file names for finishing quests. Remaining exceptions are
 handled on a case by case basis.

screenshot: add tests for naming quest complete screenshots

Adds 7 test cases for testing the new mechanism to name the quest
complete screenshot. Two test cases are quests that need no exception
handling. Five test cases are select quests which take extra code,
implemented in my previous commit, to refine the file name.

screenshot: add default case for naming quest complete screenshots

In the unlikely event that a new or updated quest reward scroll text
does not match either regex, return a default string, until the code
accounts for the new text.

afterCommit.message:
screenshot: refine code, add test for naming quest complete screenshots

Implements changes as requested, including adding a test case for when
the quest cannot be found. The reward scroll text to use for this case
should both be a reasonable message to expect and not match either regex
 used to match the input. The format used is "quest name" "past tense
 irregular verb".
 Also removes a line that, when running tests, now causes unnecessary
 stubbings error when previously it seemed necessary to run tests.
